# MiniAppBench: Evaluating Shift from Text to Interactive HTML Responses in LLM Assistants

LLM responses are static text: explanations, lists, code blocks. But users often need *interactive tools*, not passive information. MiniAppBench introduces a new paradigm: LLMs generate self-contained HTML applications—complete with styling, interactivity, and logic—that users can immediately use. A calculator explanation becomes an actual calculator. A regex guide becomes an interactive regex tester. A financial analysis becomes an embedded spreadsheet.

This skill teaches generating production-ready HTML/CSS/JavaScript applications that solve user problems interactively. Rather than explaining how to use a tool, the assistant *becomes* the tool.

## Core Insight

Traditional LLM responses maximize information density in minimal text: "To calculate compound interest, use the formula...". Users then need to implement or find a tool themselves. Interactive HTML responses flip this: the assistant generates a working tool immediately, inline, with live updates and visual feedback.

The breakthrough is recognizing that LLMs are increasingly good at generating *valid, executable HTML/CSS/JavaScript*. Modern LLMs can produce self-contained applications that actually work—no backend required. This enables a new interaction pattern: specification → working micro-app → immediate user value.

Key advantages: (1) Users get working tools without leaving conversation, (2) Complex explanations become intuitive demos, (3) Context savings—show vs. tell, (4) Verification—users see the tool work, not just read about it.

The tradeoff: HTML generation is more complex than text, and bad HTML breaks functionality. This skill focuses on generating *reliable, maintainable* HTML applications.

## Implementation

```python
import json
from typing import Dict, List, Optional
from dataclasses import dataclass, field
from enum import Enum
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod


class AppType(Enum):
    """Categories of mini-apps LLMs can generate."""
    CALCULATOR = "calculator"           # Math/formula tools
    DATA_VISUALIZER = "visualizer"      # Charts, graphs, data display
    FORM_TOOL = "form_tool"             # Dynamic forms, validators
    SIMULATOR = "simulator"             # Simulations, interactive demos
    UTILITY = "utility"                 # Text tools, converters, generators
    PLANNER = "planner"                 # Scheduling, task management
    ANALYZER = "analyzer"               # Data analysis, metrics
    EDITOR = "editor"                   # Text/code editors, markup


@dataclass
class HTMLApp:
    """Generated HTML mini-application."""
    title: str
    app_type: AppType
    description: str
    html_content: str                   # Full valid HTML
    css_embedded: str                   # CSS (embedded or in <style>)
    javascript_embedded: str            # JS (embedded or in <script>)
    required_libraries: List[str] = field(default_factory=list)  # e.g., ["chart.js"]
    input_params: Dict[str, str] = field(default_factory=dict)  # Configurable parameters
    accessibility_score: float = 0.8    # 0-1, WCAG compliance
    mobile_responsive: bool = True

    def to_html_page(self) -> str:
        """Render as standalone HTML page."""
        libs_html = ""
        for lib in self.required_libraries:
            libs_html += f'    <script src="{lib}"></script>\n'

        return f"""<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>{self.title}</title>
{libs_html}
    <style>
{self.css_embedded}
    </style>
</head>
<body>
{self.html_content}
    <script>
{self.javascript_embedded}
    </script>
</body>
</html>"""

    def get_summary(self) -> str:
        """Get user-facing summary."""
        return f"""## {self.title}

{self.description}

**Type:** {self.app_type.value}
**Mobile Responsive:** {'Yes' if self.mobile_responsive else 'No'}
**External Libraries:** {', '.join(self.required_libraries) if self.required_libraries else 'None'}
"""


class HTMLAppGenerator:
    """Generate interactive HTML mini-applications."""

    def __init__(self):
        self.templates = self._load_templates()
        self.validation_rules = self._setup_validation()

    def _load_templates(self) -> Dict[AppType, str]:
        """Load generation templates for each app type."""
        return {
            AppType.CALCULATOR: self._template_calculator(),
            AppType.FORM_TOOL: self._template_form(),
            AppType.DATA_VISUALIZER: self._template_visualizer(),
        }

    def _template_calculator(self) -> str:
        """Template for calculator-type apps."""
        return """
<div class="calculator-container">
    <h2>{{ title }}</h2>
    <div class="inputs">
        {{ input_fields }}
    </div>
    <div class="controls">
        <button onclick="calculate()">Calculate</button>
        <button onclick="reset()">Reset</button>
    </div>
    <div class="result">
        <p id="result-text"></p>
    </div>
</div>
"""

    def _template_form(self) -> str:
        """Template for form-type apps."""
        return """
<div class="form-container">
    <h2>{{ title }}</h2>
    <form id="dynamic-form">
        {{ form_fields }}
    </form>
    <div class="actions">
        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
        <button type="reset">Clear</button>
    </div>
    <div id="submission-result"></div>
</div>
"""

    def _template_visualizer(self) -> str:
        """Template for data visualization apps."""
        return """
<div class="visualizer-container">
    <h2>{{ title }}</h2>
    <div class="controls">
        {{ control_inputs }}
    </div>
    <div id="chart-container" class="chart"></div>
</div>
"""

    def _setup_validation(self) -> Dict[str, callable]:
        """Validation rules for generated HTML."""
        return {
            "html_valid": self._validate_html,
            "javascript_safe": self._validate_javascript,
            "css_valid": self._validate_css,
            "responsive": self._validate_responsive,
            "accessible": self._validate_accessible
        }

    def generate_app(
        self,
        spec: str,
        app_type: AppType = AppType.UTILITY
    ) -> HTMLApp:
        """
        Generate an interactive HTML app from specification.

        Args:
            spec: User's description of desired app
            app_type: Category of app to generate

        Returns:
            HTMLApp object with complete implementation
        """
        # In practice: LLM generates HTML, CSS, JS based on spec
        # Here: example calculator implementation

        if "calcul" in spec.lower() or "compute" in spec.lower():
            app = self._generate_calculator_app(spec)
        elif "form" in spec.lower() or "input" in spec.lower():
            app = self._generate_form_app(spec)
        elif "chart" in spec.lower() or "graph" in spec.lower():
            app = self._generate_visualizer_app(spec)
        else:
            app = self._generate_utility_app(spec)

        # Validate generated app
        validation_results = self.validate_app(app)
        app.accessibility_score = validation_results.get("accessibility", 0.8)

        return app

    def _generate_calculator_app(self, spec: str) -> HTMLApp:
        """Generate a calculator-type app."""

        html_content = """
<div class="calculator-container">
    <h2>Interactive Calculator</h2>
    <div class="inputs">
        <label>Number 1: <input type="number" id="num1" placeholder="Enter first number"></label>
        <label>Number 2: <input type="number" id="num2" placeholder="Enter second number"></label>
        <label>Operation:
            <select id="operation">
                <option value="add">Add (+)</option>
                <option value="subtract">Subtract (-)</option>
                <option value="multiply">Multiply (×)</option>
                <option value="divide">Divide (÷)</option>
            </select>
        </label>
    </div>
    <div class="controls">
        <button onclick="calculate()">Calculate</button>
        <button onclick="reset()">Reset</button>
    </div>
    <div class="result">
        <p id="result-text"></p>
    </div>
</div>
"""

        css = """
.calculator-container {
    max-width: 400px;
    margin: 20px auto;
    padding: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    border-radius: 8px;
    font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto;
}

.inputs {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 15px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
}

.inputs label {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 5px;
}

.inputs input,
.inputs select {
    padding: 10px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    border-radius: 4px;
    font-size: 14px;
}

.controls {
    display: flex;
    gap: 10px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
}

button {
    flex: 1;
    padding: 10px;
    background-color: #0066cc;
    color: white;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 4px;
    cursor: pointer;
    font-weight: bold;
}

button:hover {
    background-color: #0052a3;
}

.result {
    padding: 15px;
    background-color: #f5f5f5;
    border-radius: 4px;
    text-align: center;
}

#result-text {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 18px;
    font-weight: bold;
    color: #333;
}

@media (max-width: 600px) {
    .calculator-container {
        margin: 10px;
        padding: 15px;
    }

    .controls {
        flex-direction: column;
    }
}
"""

        javascript = """
function calculate() {
    const num1 = parseFloat(document.getElementById('num1').value);
    const num2 = parseFloat(document.getElementById('num2').value);
    const operation = document.getElementById('operation').value;
    const resultEl = document.getElementById('result-text');

    if (isNaN(num1) || isNaN(num2)) {
        resultEl.textContent = 'Please enter valid numbers';
        return;
    }

    let result;
    switch(operation) {
        case 'add':
            result = num1 + num2;
            break;
        case 'subtract':
            result = num1 - num2;
            break;
        case 'multiply':
            result = num1 * num2;
            break;
        case 'divide':
            if (num2 === 0) {
                resultEl.textContent = 'Cannot divide by zero';
                return;
            }
            result = num1 / num2;
            break;
    }

    resultEl.textContent = `Result: ${result.toFixed(2)}`;
}

function reset() {
    document.getElementById('num1').value = '';
    document.getElementById('num2').value = '';
    document.getElementById('operation').value = 'add';
    document.getElementById('result-text').textContent = '';
}

// Allow Enter key to calculate
document.addEventListener('keypress', function(e) {
    if (e.key === 'Enter') calculate();
});
"""

        return HTMLApp(
            title="Interactive Calculator",
            app_type=AppType.CALCULATOR,
            description="Simple calculator supporting basic arithmetic operations",
            html_content=html_content,
            css_embedded=css,
            javascript_embedded=javascript,
            mobile_responsive=True
        )

    def _generate_form_app(self, spec: str) -> HTMLApp:
        """Generate a form-type app."""
        return HTMLApp(
            title="Dynamic Form",
            app_type=AppType.FORM_TOOL,
            description=spec,
            html_content="<form></form>",
            css_embedded="",
            javascript_embedded="",
        )

    def _generate_visualizer_app(self, spec: str) -> HTMLApp:
        """Generate a visualization app."""
        return HTMLApp(
            title="Data Visualizer",
            app_type=AppType.DATA_VISUALIZER,
            description=spec,
            html_content="<div id='chart'></div>",
            css_embedded="",
            javascript_embedded="",
            required_libraries=["https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js"]
        )

    def _generate_utility_app(self, spec: str) -> HTMLApp:
        """Generate a utility app."""
        return HTMLApp(
            title="Utility Tool",
            app_type=AppType.UTILITY,
            description=spec,
            html_content="<div></div>",
            css_embedded="",
            javascript_embedded="",
        )

    def validate_app(self, app: HTMLApp) -> Dict[str, any]:
        """Validate generated app for quality."""
        results = {
            "html_valid": self._validate_html(app.html_content),
            "javascript_safe": self._validate_javascript(app.javascript_embedded),
            "css_valid": self._validate_css(app.css_embedded),
            "responsive": self._validate_responsive(app),
            "accessible": self._validate_accessible(app.html_content),
        }

        # Calculate overall quality score
        results["overall_score"] = sum(results.values()) / len(results)

        return results

    def _validate_html(self, html: str) -> bool:
        """Check HTML validity."""
        return "<" in html and ">" in html and html.count("<") == html.count(">")

    def _validate_javascript(self, js: str) -> bool:
        """Check JavaScript safety—block dangerous patterns."""
        dangerous = ["eval(", "innerHTML", "dangerouslySetInnerHTML"]
        return not any(pattern in js for pattern in dangerous)

    def _validate_css(self, css: str) -> bool:
        """Check CSS validity."""
        return "{" in css and "}" in css

    def _validate_responsive(self, app: HTMLApp) -> bool:
        """Check responsive design."""
        return "@media" in app.css_embedded or app.mobile_responsive

    def _validate_accessible(self, html: str) -> bool:
        """Check accessibility features."""
        has_labels = "<label" in html
        has_alt = 'alt="' in html or "<img" not in html
        return has_labels or has_alt


class AppEmbedding:
    """Embed generated apps in conversation responses."""

    @staticmethod
    def create_response_with_app(
        introduction: str,
        app: HTMLApp,
        follow_up: str = ""
    ) -> str:
        """Create a conversational response that includes an app."""

        html_page = app.to_html_page()

        response = f"""{introduction}

<div class="embedded-app-container">
{html_page}
</div>

{follow_up}
"""
        return response

    @staticmethod
    def create_downloadable_link(app: HTMLApp) -> str:
        """Generate link for user to download app."""
        return f"""
[Download {app.title}](data:text/html;base64,{encode_to_base64(app.to_html_page())})
"""


def encode_to_base64(text: str) -> str:
    """Encode text to base64 for data: URIs."""
    import base64
    return base64.b64encode(text.encode()).decode()
```

## Practical Guidance

| Use Case | Trigger Phrase | App Type |
|----------|---|---|
| **Financial planning** | "Help me calculate compound interest / retirement savings" | CALCULATOR |
| **Data exploration** | "Visualize this data / Show a chart of..." | DATA_VISUALIZER |
| **Quick tools** | "Build a [thing] calculator/converter/tool" | CALCULATOR or UTILITY |
| **Form validation** | "Create a form that checks for..." | FORM_TOOL |
| **Interactive learning** | "Explain with a demo / interactive example" | SIMULATOR |
| **Process automation** | "Create a workflow tool for..." | FORM_TOOL or PLANNER |
| **Content creation** | "Build a generator for..." | UTILITY or EDITOR |

**Generation Guidelines:**
- Start simple: single-page HTML, no dependencies unless necessary
- Mobile-first CSS: test at 320px and 1024px widths
- Accessibility: all inputs have labels, color isn't sole indicator, 4.5:1 contrast
- Error handling: graceful failures, clear user feedback, no console errors
- Responsiveness: media queries for breakpoints at 768px, 1024px

**Best Practices:**
- Embed only when it *reduces* explanation burden—an interactive demo beats pages of text
- Validate before delivering—users expect working tools, not broken code
- Keep scope small—micro-apps are easier to use than monolithic tools
- Include usage guidance—even intuitive tools benefit from a sentence about primary use

**Failure Modes:**
- Over-complex apps—too much functionality breaks usability; split into smaller tools
- Buggy JavaScript—test all input paths; validate form data; handle edge cases
- Mobile failures—responsive CSS doesn't work on small screens; test aggressively
- Unnecessary libraries—each external script is a dependency; prefer vanilla JS

## Reference

Based on "MiniAppBench: Evaluating Shift from Text to Interactive HTML Responses in LLM Assistants" (arXiv:2503.00005, Mar 11, 2025).
